This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already very widespread, but provides details that fossils cannot generally provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was brown chestnut on top and pale or carotene-colored on the underside.
This discovery also allows us to better understand the evolution of feathers in birds.
Given that dinosaur feathers do not have a fully developed shaft, which is called a rachis, but show other characteristics peculiar to feathers – barbs and barbules – researchers have deduced that the rachis was probably an evolutionary later development of these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used in flight but rather for regulation or the display of temperature. Researchers have suggested that, even if it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the specimen shows adult plumage and not down of a chick.
The scientists specify that it is certainly the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the sample reveals a plumage belonging to an adult individual, and not to a young one.
